<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1156,353,585]" box="[160,275,353,378]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">
<heading box="[160,275,353,378]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" reason="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,275,353,378]" inLineHeading="true" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" reason="3">Comment</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1156,353,585]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">
Apparently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Young DA" box="[298,441,388,412]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" pagination="1 - 1135" refId="ref13480" refString="Young DA. 1977. Taxonomic study of the Cicadellinae (Homoptera: Cicadellidae). Part 2, New World Cicadellini and the genus Cicadella. Tech Bull N C Agric Exp Stn. 239: 1 - 1135." type="journal article" year="1977">Young (1977</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 435) based on specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leal &amp; Creão-Duarte &amp; Mejdalani" authorityYear="2016" box="[822,989,388,412]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scopogonalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amazonensis">
<emphasis box="[822,989,388,412]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">S. amazonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
his interpretation of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leal" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[243,397,423,447]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scopogonalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subolivacea">
<emphasis box="[243,397,423,447]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">S. subolivacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Chanchamayo, 
<collectingCountry box="[641,695,423,447]" name="Peru" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[755,865,423,447]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">paratypes</typeStatus>
from Acre state have the pronotum almost completely yellow, with the posterior part light green. The fore wings also present a less intense tonality of green than the specimens from Amazonas do. However, the comparison of the male genitalia of specimens from both states support the hypothesis that they belong to the same species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1156,633,796]" box="[160,386,633,658]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">
<heading box="[160,386,633,658]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" reason="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,386,633,658]" inLineHeading="true" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" reason="3">Comparative notes</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1156,633,796]" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leal" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[426,579,668,692]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scopogonalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subolivacea">
<emphasis box="[426,579,668,692]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">S. subolivacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the latter by the small and semifused dentiform processes of the ventral aedeagal portion (
<figureCitation box="[885,997,703,727]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1100,1123]" captionTargetBox="[179,1136,138,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-199@7.[178,1138,137,1069]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 6. Scopogonalia amazonensis sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; (B) male pygofer, lateral view; (C) valve and subgenital plates, ventral view; (D) styles and connective, dorsal view; (E) aedeagus and paraphyses, lateral view; (F) apex of aedeagus, ventral view; (G) female abdominal sternite VII, ventral view; (H) valvula II of ovipositor, lateral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm; B–D = 0.5 mm; E = 0.25 mm; F = 0.13 mm; G–H = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206537" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206537/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">Figure 6E</figureCitation>
) and by the narrower wing-shaped lateral processes (
<figureCitation box="[634,768,737,761]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1100,1123]" captionTargetBox="[179,1136,138,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-199@7.[178,1138,137,1069]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 6. Scopogonalia amazonensis sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; (B) male pygofer, lateral view; (C) valve and subgenital plates, ventral view; (D) styles and connective, dorsal view; (E) aedeagus and paraphyses, lateral view; (F) apex of aedeagus, ventral view; (G) female abdominal sternite VII, ventral view; (H) valvula II of ovipositor, lateral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm; B–D = 0.5 mm; E = 0.25 mm; F = 0.13 mm; G–H = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206537" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206537/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">Figure 6E–F</figureCitation>
). The rami of the paraphyses are also longer in the new species than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leal" baseAuthorityYear="2014" box="[607,761,772,796]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Scopogonalia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subolivacea">
<emphasis box="[607,761,772,796]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">S. subolivacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[778,884,772,796]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="7.[160,225,1100,1123]" captionTargetBox="[179,1136,138,1067]" captionTargetId="figure-199@7.[178,1138,137,1069]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 6. Scopogonalia amazonensis sp. nov. (A) Dorsal habitus; (B) male pygofer, lateral view; (C) valve and subgenital plates, ventral view; (D) styles and connective, dorsal view; (E) aedeagus and paraphyses, lateral view; (F) apex of aedeagus, ventral view; (G) female abdominal sternite VII, ventral view; (H) valvula II of ovipositor, lateral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm; B–D = 0.5 mm; E = 0.25 mm; F = 0.13 mm; G–H = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5206537" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5206537/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="1531">Figure 6E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
